<!-- * section :- The <section> element represents a generic section of a document or application.
* artical :- The <article> element represents a independent item section of content. 
* div :-  The <div> element has no special meaning at all. -->


<!-- 12. What is the purpose of the <head> section in HTML? -->

<!-- * A simple HTML document, with a <title> tag inside the head section:
     * The HTML <head> element is a container for the following elements: <title>, <style>, <meta>, <link>, <script>, and <base>.
     * The <head> element is a container for metadata (data about data) and is placed between the <html> tag and the <body> tag.
     * Metadata is data about the HTML document. -->




<!-- 13. How do you embed audio and video in HTML? -->

<!-- <audio controls>
    <source src="audio.mp3" type="audio/mpeg">
</audio> -->

<!-- <video width="640" height="360" controls>
    <source src="video.mp4" type="video/mp4">
</video> -->


<!-- 14. Describe the purpose of the alt attribute in the <img> tag. -->

<!-- The alt attribute provides alternative information for an image if a user for some reason cannot view it (because of slow connection, an error in the src attribute, or if the user uses a screen reader). -->


<!-- 15. Explain the differences between <iframe>, <object>, and <embed> tags. -->

<!-- Flexibility: <iframe> is the most flexible, allowing you to embed entire web pages. 
                 <object> is versatile, supporting various types of media, while 
                 <embed> is specific for embedding multimedia and interactive elements.

    Fallback Content: <iframe> doesn’t provide a built-in way to specify fallback content. 
                      <object> allows fallback contbetween its opening and closing tags. 
                      <embed> does not have built-in fallback content and should be used with alternatmethods for providing fallback content if needed.

    Security: <iframe> is the most secure for embedding content from different origins due to its sandboxing capabilities. 
              <object> and <embed> can potentially pose security risks, especially when embedding interactive or plugin-based content. -->



