<!-- * <strong></strong> :-
1. The text inside this tag is bold
2. The <strong> tag is used to define text with strong importance
3. the strong tag semantically emphasizes on the important word or section of words while

* <b></b> :-
1. Its makes any text bold.
2. The bold (<b>) tag specifies bold text without any extra importance.
3. the bold tag is just offset text conventionally styled in bold -->



<!-- 19. What is the importance of the title attribute in HTML elements? -->

<!-- * The title attribute specifies extra information about an element. 
     * The information is most often shown as a tooltip text when the mouse moves over the element. -->


<!-- 20. What is the use of the <table> tag? How would you create a table with proper structure in HTML? -->

<!-- The <table> tag defines an HTML table. An HTML table consists of one <table> element and one or more <tr>, <th>, and <td> elements. 
    The <tr> element defines a table row, 
    the <th> element defines a table header, 
    the <td> element defines a table cell. -->

<!-- <table>
        <tr>
          <th>Month</th>
          <th>Savings</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>January</td>
          <td>$100</td>
        </tr>
      </table> -->


<!-- 21. Describe the differences between <link>, <script>, and <style> tags in HTML. -->

<!--     * <link> is used for linking external resources, primarily stylesheets.
         * <script> is used for embedding or referencing JavaScript code, either externally or inline.
         * <style> is used for defining internal CSS within the HTML document -->


<!-- 22. What is the purpose of the href attribute in anchor <a> tags? -->

<!-- * The href attribute specifies the URL of the page the link goes to.
     * If the href attribute is not present, the <a> tag will not be a hyperlink.
     * <a href="URL">Link Text</a> -->


<!-- 23. Explain the use of the rel attribute in HTML. -->

<!-- * The rel attribute specifies the relationship between the current document and the linked document.
     * Only used if the href attribute is present.
     * <a rel="value"></a> -->


<!-- 24. Describe the differences between inline, block, and inline-block elements in HTML. -->

<!-- * Inline Elements:-
      1. Do not start on a new line.
      2. Only take up as much width as necessary.
      3. Cannot have a specific width or height.
      4. <span>, <a>, <strong>, <em>, <img>

    * Block Elements:-
      1. Start on a new line.
      2. Take up the full available width by default.
      3. Can have specific width and height.
      4. <div>, <p>, <h1>, <ul>, <li>

    * Inline-Block Elements:-
      1. Do not start on a new line.
      2. Can have specific width and height.
      3. Flow within text like inline elements but allow for block-level styling properties.
      4. <span> (with CSS display: inline-block;), <img> (with CSS display: inline-block;) -->


