<!-- 33. Explain the purpose and differences between <main> and <div> tags in HTML5. -->

<!-- <main>  :- 
         is a semantic element representing the main content of the document. 
         It provides semantic clarity for assistive technologies and helps define the core content of the page.

    <div>  :-
         * on the other hand, is a generic container used for styling and layout purposes. 
         * It does not convey any specific meaning and is often used in conjunction with CSS for applying styles or structuring content for
           scripting purposes. -->


<!-- 34. What is the importance of the doctype declaration in HTML? -->

<!-- * All HTML documents must start with a <!DOCTYPE> declaration.
     * The declaration is not an HTML tag. It is an "information" to the browser about what document type to expect.
     * <!DOCTYPE html> -->


<!-- 35. Describe the significance of the <figure> and <figcaption> elements in HTML. -->

<!-- <figure> :- 
    * The <figure> tag specifies self-contained content, like illustrations, diagrams, photos, code listings, etc.
    * Use a <figure> element to mark up a photo in a document, and a <figcaption> element to define a caption for the photo:

   <figcaption> :- 
    * The <figcaption> tag defines a caption for a <figure> element.
    * The <figcaption> element can be placed as the first or last child of the <figure> element. -->


<!-- 36. Explain the difference between <em> and <i> tags in HTML. -->

<!-- <em> :-  
        * The <em> element is used to emphasize text, indicating that the enclosed text has stress or importance within the context of the surrounding text. 
        * When a browser or a screen reader encounters text wrapped in <em> tags, it typically emphasizes that text, usually by rendering it in italics by default.

    <i> :- 
        * The <i> element, on the other hand, is used to apply stylistic italic formatting to the enclosed text without implying any specific meaning or emphasis. 
        * It is typically used for presentational purposes when the text needs to be italicized for visual aesthetics, but there is no semantic importance attached to the italicized text. -->


<!-- 37. How does HTML support responsive images? -->

<!-- * The most common use of the <picture> element will be for images used in responsive designs. 
     * Instead of having one image that is scaled up or down based on the viewport width, multiple images can be designed to more nicely fill the browser viewport. -->


<!-- 38. What is the role of the <time> element in HTML5? -->

<!-- * The <time> tag defines a specific time (or datetime).
         * The datetime attribute of this element is used translate the time into a machine-readable format so that browsers can offer to add date reminders through the user's calendar, and search engines can produce smarter search results. -->


<!-- 39. How does HTML support microdata and structured data? -->

<!-- * inline HTML microdata was only used to nest metadata within the HTML content itself and is no longer the preferred method of adding schema to a page. 
     * Now, structured data is implemented into a website's code using JSON-LD as the preferred method. -->


<!-- 40. Explain the differences between <input type="text">, <input type="password">, and <input type="email">. -->

<!-- <input type="text"> :-
    * 1. This input type is used for general text input.
    * 2. It does not provide any specific validation for the entered text.
   
<input type="password">  :-
    * 1. This input type is designed for sensitive data such as passwords.
    * 2. It is specifically meant for sensitive information and is commonly used in login forms.
   
<input type="email">     :-
    * 1. This input type is used for email addresses.
    * 2. Browsers often provide specific keyboard layouts for email input fields on mobile devices to make it easier for users to enter email addresses.
 -->


<!-- 41. What are the uses of the <details> and <summary> elements in HTML? -->

<!-- The <summary> tag defines a visible heading for the <details> element. The heading can be clicked to view/hide the details.
    Note: The <summary> element should be the first child element of the <details> element. -->


<!-- 42. Describe the differences between <ol>, <ul>, and <dl> elements in HTML. -->

<!-- * <ol> is for ordered lists, where items are numbered.
     * <ul> is for unordered lists, where items are bulleted or marked with another symbol.
     * <dl> is for description lists, where each term is followed by a definition or description. -->


<!-- 43. Describe the uses and differences between <abbr>, <acronym>, and <cite> in HTML. -->

<!-- * <abbr> is used for abbreviations and acronyms, providing additional information about the abbreviated term.
     * <acronym> (obsolete) served a similar purpose to <abbr> but has been deprecated in favor of using <abbr>.Not Supported in HTML5.
     * <cite> is used to indicate the title of a creative work, such as books, movies, or songs, and is often used to cite the source of a    quotation.The text in the <cite> element usually renders in italic. -->


<!-- 44. Explain the role of the async and defer attributes when loading scripts in HTML. -->

<!-- * Use async when the script can be executed independently of other scripts and does not depend on the order of execution or the state of the DOM.
* <script src="script.js" async></script> -->
<!-- * Use defer when the script depends on the order of execution or relies on interactions with the DOM. Deferred scripts provide a way to ensure scripts are executed in order while not blocking the parsing of the HTML document.
* <script src="script.js" defer></script> -->


<!-- 45. Explain the concept of the viewport in HTML and its importance for responsive design. -->

<!-- <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"> 
     
* The viewport is the user's visible area of a web page. 
* The viewport varies with the device, and will be smaller on a mobile phone than on a computer screen. 
* Before tablets and mobile phones, web pages were designed only for computer screens, and it was common for web pages to have a static design and a fixed size. -->